    "location": "Ireland",
    "status": "implementing",
    "severity": {
      "score": 4,
      "rationale": "Universal application for designated platform users [+1], criminal penalties for platforms (fines up to EUR 20M or 10% revenue) [+1], biometric/ID document collection for age verification [+1], digital exclusion (requires ID documents/smartphone) [+1], no judicial oversight (platforms decide verification methods) [+1], mission creep from pornography to 'harmful content' [+0.5]. Total exceeds 5 - 4/5"
    },
    "categories": ["age_verification", "digital_id", "biometric_collection"],
    "jurisdiction": "National",
    "description": "Mandatory age verification for video-sharing platforms headquartered in Ireland (Facebook, Instagram, TikTok, YouTube, X, etc.). Requires 'effective age assurance' for adult content - self-declaration not sufficient. Part A active from November 2024, Part B (age verification) from July 2025.",
    "sources": [
      {
        "url": "https://www.cnam.ie/coimisiun-na-mean-adopts-final-online-safety-code/",
        "type": "primary",
        "description": "Coimisiun na Mean official adoption of Online Safety Code"
      },
      {
        "url": "https://www.rte.ie/news/2025/0721/1524435-online-platform-verification/",
        "type": "news",
        "description": "RTE News - Age verification rules implementation July 2025"
      },
      {
        "url": "https://childrensrights.ie/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Online-Safety-Monitor-2025.pdf",
        "type": "civil_society",
        "description": "Children's Rights Alliance analysis of Online Safety Code gaps"
      },
      {
        "url": "https://5rightsfoundation.com/resource/irish-online-safety-code/",
        "type": "civil_society",
        "description": "5Rights Foundation analysis of age verification requirements"
      }
    ],
    "notes": "Major civil liberties concerns: (1) Mandatory age verification requires government ID or biometric facial recognition - creates surveillance infrastructure; (2) Platforms designated: Facebook, Instagram, YouTube, TikTok, LinkedIn, X, Pinterest, Tumblr, Reddit (Reddit de-designated May 2025); (3) 'Adult-only content' definition vague - platforms decide what requires verification; (4) Children's data collected for age verification cannot be used for commercial purposes BUT retention periods unclear; (5) No clear standards for age assurance - platforms can choose credit cards, AI facial analysis, behavioral profiling; (6) 9-month implementation delay (July 2025) left children unprotected per Children's Rights Alliance. Opposition: Tumblr and Reddit took unsuccessful High Court actions. Privacy campaigners concerned about sensitive data storage. Digital Rights Ireland monitoring implementation. Workers' concern: Platform workers (content moderators) face increased exposure to traumatic content; age verification creates barriers to anonymous worker organizing online."
  },
  {
    "id": "IE-2011-PSC",
    "commonName": "Public Services Card (Biometric ID Database)",
    "legalName": "Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005 (as amended) - Public Services Card provisions",
    "location": "Ireland",
    "status": "challenged",
    "severity": {
      "score": 4,
      "rationale": "Universal application (millions of citizens for essential services) [+1], irreversible biometric collection (facial templates) [+1], digital exclusion (required for welfare, childcare, driving licenses) [+1], no judicial oversight for data access [+1], mission creep from welfare to multiple services [+1]. No criminal penalties directly. Total: 5/5 but reduced to 4 due to ongoing challenge."
    },
    "categories": ["digital_id", "biometric_collection"],
    "jurisdiction": "National",
    "description": "National ID card with biometric facial recognition templates required for accessing public services including welfare payments, driving license renewals, and National Childcare Scheme. State denied biometric processing but Data Protection Commission ruled otherwise in June 2025.",
    "sources": [
      {
        "url": "https://www.irishexaminer.com/news/arid-41790617.html",
        "type": "news",
        "description": "Irish Examiner - 24 legal actions over PSC biometric data, DPC ruling"
      },
      {
        "url": "https://digitalfreedomfund.org/case-studies/irelands-id-card-for-accessing-public-services/",
        "type": "civil_society",
        "description": "Digital Freedom Fund - Digital Rights Ireland challenge to PSC"
      },
      {
        "url": "https://www.digitalrights.ie/campaigns/mass-surveillance/",
        "type": "civil_society",
        "description": "Digital Rights Ireland - PSC mass surveillance campaign"
      }
    ],
    "notes": "LONG-RUNNING CIVIL LIBERTIES BATTLE. Key events: (1) 2021: DPC investigation began after Digital Rights Ireland complaint; (2) June 2025: DPC ruled PSC uses biometric data, fined State EUR 550,000, ordered discontinuation within 9 months unless lawful basis found; (3) State appealed July 2025 - appeal ongoing; (4) 24 outstanding Circuit Court cases by citizens; (5) Previous battle over mandatory nature ended in 2021 settlement. Current status: Card still widely used while appeal pending. Concerns: (1) State denied biometric processing for years claiming 'arithmetic template' not biometric - DPC rejected this; (2) Function creep from welfare to driving licenses, childcare, other services; (3) No clear legal basis for biometric processing per DPC; (4) Millions of citizens' facial templates in database. Opposition: Digital Rights Ireland leading legal challenge. 24 individual court cases pending. Workers' concern: Required for accessing employment-related services (childcare support), creates surveillance infrastructure that could be used against undocumented workers."
  },
