      },
      {
        "url": "https://www.digitalrights.ie/campaigns/mass-surveillance/",
        "type": "civil_society",
        "description": "Digital Rights Ireland - Mobile phone data retention challenge"
      },
      {
        "url": "https://www.lawsociety.ie/gazette/top-stories/2024/june/mcentee-obtains-new-order-on-data-retention",
        "type": "news",
        "description": "Law Society Gazette - Data retention order analysis"
      }
    ],
    "notes": "IMPLEMENTS MASS SURVEILLANCE DESPITE CJEU RULINGS. Background: (1) 2006: DRI challenged data retention leading to CJEU Digital Rights Ireland ruling striking down EU Data Retention Directive; (2) 2022: Act amended after CJEU Tele2 ruling; (3) June 2023: First Section 3A order granted; (4) June 2024: Second order granted for 12 months. Current regime: (1) General and indiscriminate retention permitted only for 'state security'; (2) Minister applies ex parte to High Court judge designated by President of High Court; (3) Access to retained data requires District Court authorization; (4) Annual report to Taoiseach by designated High Court judge. Concerns: (1) 'State security' justification is catch-all - no transparency about specific threats; (2) Ex parte applications mean no opposing arguments heard; (3) Graham Dwyer case established CJEU limits but Ireland using 'state security' exception; (4) Identity of every person you phone/text/email retained with location data. Opposition: Digital Rights Ireland ongoing litigation to strike down national laws. Workers' concern: Mass surveillance chills worker organizing, union communications, solidarity networks - metadata reveals relationships and meeting locations."
  },

