      }
    ],
    "notes": "DE FACTO MANDATORY DIGITAL ID. While technically voluntary, itsme is: (1) Used by 90% of Belgian adult residents; (2) Required for most online banking; (3) Used for government services via MyGov.be; (4) Expanded to 30 European countries for cross-border authentication; (5) Now accepted by INPI France for company formalities. Corporate structure: Founded by Belgian banks (KBC, ING, Belfius, BNP Paribas Fortis) and telecoms (Telenet, Proximus, Orange). FPIM (Belgian government investment fund) acquired stake 2021 - partial nationalization. Acquired Dutch iDIN in 2025 - expansion to Netherlands. Concerns: (1) Private sector control of essential identity infrastructure; (2) Biometric verification (fingerprint/face) for high-assurance transactions; (3) Data stored in Europe but corporate profit motive; (4) Network effects make it effectively mandatory; (5) Expansion to employment/HR verification. Opposition: Limited civil society opposition due to perceived convenience. Privacy by design claims but centralization concerns. Workers' concern: Required for accessing employment platforms, banking, social services - undocumented workers face exclusion. Union perspective: Convenient but dependency on private infrastructure problematic."
  },
